Exercise 2: edge List to bipartite

This should be very straightforward, as the code was included in the exercise text (repeated below):

weighted <- read.csv(file.choose()) # pop-up window to select `medgarden.csv`

bipart.med <- weighted %>%
  group_by(plant, pollinator) %>%
  tally() %>%
  pivot_wider(id_cols = c("plant"), # plants are the rows
              names_from = pollinator, # names of new columns: unique pollinators
              values_from = n, # values in the matrix from tallied interactions
              values_fill = 0) # if no value, enter zero (otherwise NA)

Exercise 3: plotting with visweb

Using the medgarden data you put into matrix form (now called bipart.med):

  • plot via visweb:
    • with type = "none"
    • with type = "nested"
    • with type = "diagonal"

First, change formatting of bipart.med as included in the exercise:

# save plant names
plant = bipart.med$plant
# remove plant column
bipart.med = bipart.med[,-1]
# convert to matrix
bipart.med = as.matrix(bipart.med)
# add plants to row names
row.names(bipart.med) = plant
# remove `plant` variable (just to keep workspace clean)
rm(plant)

Then plot via visweb(): code and plots are below:

# none
visweb(bipart.med, type = "none")

# nested
visweb(bipart.med, type = "nested")

# diagonal
visweb(bipart.med, type = "diagonal")

note: the visweb defaults often have labels that are spaced quite far away from the matrix itself there are workarounds to that, but theyre kind of a pain and not worth getting into here.

After you have plotted with type = "diagonal": the diagonal method is set up to show modularity in the network. How many modules do you see in the med garden network? Can you comment on the modules qualitatively in terms of the organisms involved?

  • there are two modules outlined in boxes
    • (the example we showed in the slides during the meeting did not display those, as the Motten 1982 network has no noticeable modularity)
  • one of the modules is hummingbirds on one plant (Tragopogon); the other module is everything else!
    • alternatively, we could say that insects and the plants they interact with are one module, and non-insects are the other module

Optional bonus 3.1

Also straightforward, directly following the code below (included in exercise) to order the rows and columns of the bipart.med matrix:

rows = rowSums(bipart.med>0) # calculate row sums
cols = colSums(bipart.med>0) # calculate column sums
roworder = order(rows, decreasing = T) # order rows by sum
colorder = order(cols, decreasing = T) # order columns by sum
bipart.med = bipart.med[roworder,colorder] # re-order rows and cols in matrix

Re-plot with type = "none"; plot below

visweb(bipart.med, type = "none")

Exercise 10: graphical null model

Straightforward: analyze NODF for the Safariland dataset using the r2dtable null model graphically, using the code below (also included in the exercise):

data(Safariland)
Iobs <- networklevel(Safariland, index = "NODF")[[1]]
nulls <- nullmodel(web=Safariland, N = 999, method = 'r2dtable') # can take a while...
Inulls <- sapply(nulls, function(x) nestednodf(x)$statistic[3])
plot(density(Inulls), xlim = c(0, 100), lwd = 2, main = "NODF")
# plot(hist(Inulls), xlim=c(0, 100), lwd=2, main="NODF") # histogram
abline(v=Iobs, col="red", lwd=2)

Calculate the (two-tailed) \(p\)-value for the above null model analysis, using the code below:

# two-tailed p-value for permutation test with null models
pval = (min(length(which(Inulls>Iobs)), length(which(Iobs>Inulls))+1) /
          length(c(Iobs,Inulls)))*2
pval
## [1] 0.002

as indicated in the exercise, your \(p\)-value should be exactly 0.002.

how do you interpret your result? think about whether your result is statistically significant as well as the directionality of the result:

  • here the directionality of the result is that the value of NODF is lower in the empirical data (red line) than in the null model simulationsin other words, the Safariland network is LESS nested than expected by chance, as assessed with the r2dtable null model
  • since the \(p\)-value is less than 0.05, we can say that this result is statistically significant

Optional bonus 10.1

Re-run the analysis above with the swap.web null model (this is a very straightforward replacement of r2dtable with swap.web) above.

here is the code and graph for that:

data(Safariland)
Iobs <- networklevel(Safariland, index = "NODF")[[1]]
nulls <- nullmodel(web=Safariland, N = 999, method = 'swap.web') # can take a while...
Inulls <- sapply(nulls, function(x) nestednodf(x)$statistic[3])
plot(density(Inulls), xlim = c(0, 100), lwd = 2, main = "NODF")
# plot(hist(Inulls), xlim=c(0, 100), lwd=2, main="NODF") # histogram
abline(v=Iobs, col="red", lwd=2)

You should get a qualitatively different result relative to using swap.web. Describe where the empirical value falls out relative to the null models.

  • this is the same as the graph Berry showed in the workshop presentation; the empirical value falls out in the middle of the null distribution
  • this is strikingly different than the result using r2dtable, where the empirical value was much smaller than the null models

Calculate the \(p\)-value if you have time

here is the code for that:

# two-tailed p-value for permutation test with null models
pval = (min(length(which(Inulls>Iobs)), length(which(Iobs>Inulls))+1) /
          length(c(Iobs,Inulls)))*2
pval
## [1] 0.392

Because of the element of randomness in generating null networks, if you repeat this procedure multiple times or on multiple computers, you can get slight variations in the exact value, but it should be pretty close to ~0.392.

Optional bonus 10.2

Using our discussion of the correlation among network metrics, as well as our descriptions of the null models, offer an interpretation as to why the two null models (r2dtable and swap.web) yield qualitatively different results.

  • r2dtable does not hold the number of links or connectance constant. Since there are many possible interactions that could be randomly assigned, this null model tends to generate a much higher connectance than raw data
    • In this case, the connectance of the null networks is much higherabout twice as highas in the empirical network
    • one way to see that graphically would be to call visweb(as.matrix(nulls[[1]]))doing that after having run the nulls with swap.web, youll see that the connectance is identical to the Safariland network (visweb(Safariland)); if you re-run with r2dtable, youll be able to see the much greater connectance
  • as Fernanda discussed in the workshop component of correlations among network metrics, higher connectance alone inevitably increases nestedness; this is almost certainly the driver of the difference between null models in this case

Optional bonus 10.3

Try one of the null models implemented in vegan, in particular quasiswap_count. Code was included for the null models in the exercise, but that code chunk didnt include the last two lines for plotting. Here is the code (with the plotting included), and the plot below:

# alternative: use vegan::nullmodel rather than bipartite
library(vegan)
# require first setting up a null model, then separately simulating it
n.vegan <- vegan::nullmodel(Safariland, "quasiswap_count") #setup
nulls.vegan <- simulate(n.vegan, nsim = 999) #simulation
# the vegan `simulate` method returns a 3-dimensional numeric array
# so need to modify the code used for the bipartite nulls
# use `apply` rather than `sapply` with MARGIN = 3
Inulls.vegan <- apply(nulls.vegan, MARGIN = 3, 
                      FUN = function(x) nestednodf(x)$statistic[3])

# plot it
plot(density(Inulls.vegan), xlim = c(0, 100), lwd = 2, main = "NODF")
abline(v=Iobs, col="red", lwd=2)

The exercise said: You should get again a qualitatively different result relative to swap.web. This is somewhat curious as the two methods are supposed to be very similar (we are not sure why!)

  • we can see straightaway that using quasiswap_count that our empirical data appear to be significantly more nested than by chance alone, as opposed to falling out in the middle of the distribution with swap.web
  • again, because these two approaches are supposed to be similar in terms of holding connectance and degree distribution constant, it is surprising that they generate different results, and we are not sure why this is the case!
